<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
The conversion factors were determined through simulation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
studies that estimated the potential volatility of interest and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exchange rates and analyzed the implications of movements in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
those rates for the replacement costs of various types of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
interest rate and exchange rate contracts. The simulation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
studies were conducted only on rate contracts, because at the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
time the Accord was being developed activity in the derivatives 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
market was for the most part limited to these types of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
transactions. The analysis produced probability distributions of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
potential replacement costs over the remaining life of matched 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pairs of rate contracts.
<FOOTCITE>8</FOOTCITE>
 Potential future exposure was then 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
defined in terms of confidence limits for these distributions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The conversion factors were intended to be a compromise between 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
precision, on the one hand, and complexity and burden, on the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
other.
<FOOTCITE>9</FOOTCITE>
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=2 -->
8
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

</FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=2 -->
A matched pair is a pair of contracts with identical terms, with the bank the buyer of one of the contracts and the seller
of the other.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->
</FOOTNOTE>

