<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
The BSC concluded that it was not appropriate to address 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
these problems with a significant departure from the existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
methodology used in the Accord. The BSC decided that it would be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
appropriate to preserve the conversion factors existing in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Accord and add new conversion factors. Consequently, the revision 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed by the BSC retains the existing conversion factors for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rate contracts but applies new higher conversion factors to such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contracts with remaining maturities of five years and over.
<FOOTCITE>13</FOOTCITE>
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The proposal also introduces conversion factors specifically 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicable to commodity, precious metal, and equity contracts. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The new conversion factors were determined on the basis of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
simulation studies that used the same general approach that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
generated the original add-on conversion factors.
<FOOTCITE>14</FOOTCITE>

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=2 -->
13
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

</FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=2 -->
The conversion factors for rate contracts with remaining maturities of one to five years are currently applied to
any contracts with a remaining maturity of over one year.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->
</FOOTNOTE>

