<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
imposition of, and liability for, the tax on CNG. These rules 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are similar to the regulations relating to taxes on special motor fuels imposed by section 4041. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Gasohol; Tolerance Rule 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The gasoline tax rate is 18.4 cents per gallon (the regular rate). However, a reduction from the regular rate is allowed
for gasohol (a gasoline/alcohol mixture). Before January 1, 1993, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section 4081(c) treated a mixture of gasoline and alcohol as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
gasohol only if at least 10 percent of the mixture was alcohol. The rate reduction under pre-1993 law was 5.4 cents per
gallon 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for gasohol containing ethanol and 6 cents per gallon for gasohol containing alcohol other than ethanol. This was
equivalent to a subsidy of 54 cents or 60 cents per gallon of alcohol used to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
produce gasohol. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 48.4081&hyph;6(b)(2) provides a special rule for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
application of the ``at least 10 percent'' requirement by allowing a tolerance for mixtures that contain less than
10 percent 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
alcohol but at least 9.8 percent alcohol. Under the tolerance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rule, a portion of the mixture equal to the number of gallons of alcohol in the mixture multiplied by 10 is considered
to be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
gasohol. Any excess liquid in the mixture is taxed at the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regular rate. Absent the tolerance rule, pre-1993 law would have taxed the entire mixture at the regular rate. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->
